<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Select Committee -</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr style="height:23.6pt"><td style="vertical-align:top; width:357.55pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Local Government Association</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:23.6pt"><td style="vertical-align:top; width:357.55pt"><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:20pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="bmDocumentDate"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></h2></td></tr></table></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:auto" /><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About the Local Government Association (LGA)</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice of local government.  We work with councils to support, promote and improve local government.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are a politically-led, cross party organisation which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">works on behalf of councils to ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 44.25pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Councils support a streamlined system of standards for new homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. There are however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> number of issues arising from the proposals which we feel could be resolved by:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Baseline standards being adopted as national policy where there is no provision already in building regulations.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ensuring a reasonable transition period. There should be clear arrangements whereby councils which have published, or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emerging local plans, will retain any local standards set by those plans until the council undertakes a scheduled plan review.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ability for councils to retain standards in examined local plans that are the same or equivalent to those in the proposed national standard set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> without having to undertake further tests and examination</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Policies for application of new standards being incorporated into existing housing needs assessments and viability testing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> based on data that is already readily available and used by councils, rather than introducing new tests.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Introduction of a clear and transparent mechanism for councils and others to raise concerns about the impact of the national standards or to put forward ideas for revised or new standards.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ensuring a proportionate process for future new or revised standards to be added to local plans with minimal resource and cost implications for councils. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The LGA is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in discussion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the development industry about how we can ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our proposals are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> effective in reducing the number of standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how it could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">save delays and additional bureaucracy in getting appropriate standards in place.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Councils support the rationalisation of the wide range of standards for new homes that are currently promoted by different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A streamlined system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reduce complexity and duplication</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, assisting both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developers and councils.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also believe that with continued and growing demand for housing, new developments should be high quality and well-designed to meet the needs of current and future generations.  Developments which are of high quality are also likely to command greater public support and are therefore important in overcoming local opposition to development.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There is a potential tension between this and the use of standard “identikit” designs across the country to which Ministers have, we believe correctly, been resistant.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Architecture and design are also crucial as part of an area’s wider efforts to attract investment and tourism and promote locally led growth. Councils play a key role in driving high-quality design through the local planning system and it is important that councils retain this important role in order to deliver spatial aspirations for local areas. Our recent response to the Farrell Review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s call for evidence provides more information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition, the National Planning Policy Framework (NPPF) requires councils to plan the right mix of homes ‘</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">based on current and future demographic trends, market trends and the needs of different groups in the community’ </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">(paragraph</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> 50). To be able to deliver on these objectives, councils will need to be able to apply specific standards over and above those which exist in building regulations in some cases. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Councils have included standards within their local plans to ensure that housing is of good quality and meets identified local needs. A national framework that provides some flexibility for areas to choose standards that reflect local needs and circumstances would be welcome and remove much of the need for councils to have their own standards.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, there are a number of issues arising from the proposals which will need to be addressed in implementing a new national standards framework. In particular, councils have concerns about the implications for local plan-making. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Impact on local plans</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under the proposals:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any standards for new housing currently within local plans would no longer apply;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To apply any of the new standards emerging from the review, councils would need to adopt them within local plans subject to a rigorous needs assessment and viability test. This would be subject to thorough testing through the examination by the Planning Inspectorate (PINS).</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Needs and viability tests</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The existing local plan process and accompanying National Planning Policy Framework (NPPF) already provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proportionate framework for the assessment of housi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng needs and viability testing. As a result, it is unnecessary for the G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment to introduce additional tests for new standards resulting from this review.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Policies for application of new standards should therefore be incorporated into existing needs assessments and viability testing and be based on data that is already readily available and used by councils. There is potential for double-counting of costs if additional needs and viability tests are introduced for any new standards resulting from this review.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In many cases, councils may already have standards in their local plans which are the same as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or similar to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> those in the new national framework. Since these have already been accepted by the Planning Inspectorate, requiring councils to undertake further assessment and examination in order to apply the same or similar standards from a new national standard set would be an unnecessary duplication of effort</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and impose considerable costs on local government for absolutely no gain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition, councils will need to re-consult on local plans to include any of the new standards and then resubmit to PINS for “soundness” of the new policies. This will not only involve considerable time and resources for councils, but threatens to distract PINS resources from priority work of getting local plans in place.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would therefore suggest that councils should not be required to have their plans re-examined in order to incorporate the new national standards.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clarity is also needed about the legal status of a local plan where an existing standard within it is “nullified” because of a change in national policy. This could lead to an undesirable position where those parts of the plan would be treated as out of date and disregarded when decision making on planning applications was to be undertaken. This would undermine the adopted local plan document and could lead to legal challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and confusion. Therefore, a revision would need to be undertaken just to remove a standard, which would carry with it the requirement for re-consultation and examination, involving additional time and resource on councils and PINS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also foresee, in the absence of proper transition arrangements, extensive debates in front of planning inspectors and the courts, about whether national or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">existing local policy should have primacy. This uncertainty and the associated cost will benefit neither local government nor the house building industry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Finally, the delay between the deletion of existing standards from local plans and the revised plans being put in place cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ld lead to a standards ‘vacuum’. This could result </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in a decrease in the quality of new houses being built </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undesirable situation for councils, communities and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These issues could be resolved by:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.14.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Adopting the baseline standards as national policy where there is no provision already in building regulations. They can then be applied with the flexibility afforded by the planning process to make reasonable judgments on standards. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.14.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ensuring a reasonable transition period. There should be clear arrangements whereby councils which have published or emerging local plans will retain any local standards set by those plans until the council undertakes a scheduled plan review.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-25.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.14.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Allowing councils who already have standards in examined local plans that are the same or equivalent to the proposed national standard set to retain them without having to undertake further tests and examination.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Reviewing standards</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We agree with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consultation proposal that the national standards should be kept under review and support the idea of them being kept under scrutiny by a group of key partners who meet at appropriate intervals. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, there must be a clear and transparent mechanism for councils and others to raise concerns about the impact of the national standards or to put forward ideas for revised or new standards. Councils, in representing the needs of local communities should be an integral part of any review group. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consideration also needs to be given to how new or revised standards can be added to local plans and redundant ones removed in a timely fashion with minimal resource and cost implications for councils. Having to re-submit a plan to PINs every time councils want to include a new or revised standard will place unsustainable burdens on councils, add unnecessary bureaucracy and repeat problems outlined above about creating a standards vacuum.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Space</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aragraph 50 of the NPPF requires councils to provide a mix of housing, including size, to reflect local demand. To be able to deliver on that part of the NPPF, and in the absence of any national space standards being introduced, councils will need flexibility to be able to apply their own local space standards where there is an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidenced need to do so. A number of councils have already successfully introduced local space standards to all tenures of housing including Bristol City Council and Oxford City Council, which have led to improved internal environments for residents of new-builds. Others, for example Chelmsford Borough Council, have introduced minimum space standards for specific housing tenures, such as Houses in Multiple Occupation (HMOs), to prevent overcrowding and associated hazards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given that minimum space standards are not currently reflected at a national level and require significant resources to implement locally, councils would support the adoption of space standards as a baseline in the national standard set. This would enable councils to apply them with appropriate flexibility and discretion through the planning process, taking into account relevant viability concerns. However, local “grandfathering” rights should be applied for councils (and those covered by the London Plan) which already have an approved space standard. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Affordable housing</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Whilst the market will dictate minimum standards for market housing in many areas, affordable housing for rent is allocated, according to need, through councils and registered providers and c</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">hoice is limited. T</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">he market will not therefore protect standards in the same way.  In addition, affordable housing needs to provide for a higher concentration of vulnerable people and those with particular needs. Standards will be important in ensuring that new housing caters to the needs of these groups.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Under current arrangements, standards for affordable homes, including space, are regulated through conditions on grants from the Homes and Communities Agency (HCA). If that ceases to be the case, councils</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> will</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> need the flexibility to be able to set the appropriate standard level for that tenure</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">, including space. Such a process would need to</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> ensure that standards of affordable housing do not fall below a level that would be acceptable for market housing and which meet the needs of particular groups that require affordable housing. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Energy</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">consultation paper proposes that energy and carbon targets will be delivered through strengthened building regulations to move towards zero carbon homes by 2016</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">. The G</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">overnment therefore considers that there is no longer a need for separate targets to be applied through the Code for Sustainable Homes.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Under the proposals however, councils will no longer be able to require that where viable, a proportion of energy required by new development should be generated by onsite renewable sources.  </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Policies </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">regarding</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> requirements</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> on-site renewable energy generation quite properly have to go through the Local Plan </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">process and are typically subject to site-specific viability assessments.  Such policies have reduced carbon emissions and reliance upon fossil fuels, and driven innovation in the sector. In addition, setting standards for renewable energy would provide a means for ‘Allowable Solutions’ to offset carbon emissions on other sites to be delivered in the area where the development takes place, to benefit the local community. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">The LGA</span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt"> would therefore suggest that standards for on-site renewable energy should be included in the national framework that councils could adopt in a Local Plan, provided it was compatible with the requirement for viability.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Security</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Ensuring security of new housing is an excellent investment which can reduce the substantial costs of crimes – to victims and to the wider community. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Security standards are not currently covered by building regulations and we would therefore support adoption of the level 1 security standard as a default with a view to incorporating it into building regulations at the earliest opportunity.  </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.28.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">In light of higher levels of vulnerability for those in affordable housing, the Homes and Communities Agency currently apply a security standard broadly equivalent to the level 2 standard. This should continue to be the default for affordable housing.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Water</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.29.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Frutiger-Light; font-size:12pt">Given that the cost of applying the proposed water standard is only minimally above the standards required in building regulations (identified at £68), there is a compelling argument that it should be adopted as a default (in effect to replace the current building regulation). There should then be a tighter standard available for local authorities to draw upon in areas of water stress.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Impacts upon industry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.30.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is important to consider the impacts of the new standards framework upon industry.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.31.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes has brought about considerable advancements in low carbon construction industry, increasing training, development and innovation in low-carbon construction skills. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> forward their proposal to wind down the role of the Code</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there is a need to ensure that development of these skills continues and competition and innovation is encouraged. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3 October 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> LGA New Housing Development Survey 20</span><a name="_Hlt368554649"></a><a name="_Hlt368554650"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">1</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">2: </span><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/web/guest/research-housing/-/journal_content/56/10180/3592914/ARTICLE"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.local.gov.uk/web/guest/research-housing/-/journal_content/56/10180/3592914/ARTICLE</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ntu.ac.uk/apps/news/135264-15/New_housing_design_standards_co-authored_by_university_expert.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ntu.ac.uk/apps/news/135264-15/New_housing_design_standards_co-authored_by_university_expert.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Further information accessible at: </span><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=5700fa89-3426-48ed-be63-e2c3c4edb287&amp;groupId=10180"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.local.gov.uk/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=5700fa89-3426-48ed-be63-e2c3c4edb287&amp;groupId=10180</span></a></p></body></html>